 Line 1:    -   The following questions were asked during phone interviews for tenure-track faculty </strong>positions  at private liberal arts colleges and Cal State Universities.</strong>  +   ====== Faculty </strong>positions  - interview questions ======</strong>                -   ====== General ====== </strong>  +   The following questions </strong>were  asked during phone interviews for tenure-track faculty positions </strong>at  private liberal arts colleges </strong>and  Cal State Universities. </strong>( Questions in bold were frequently asked.</strong>)    -   * Why are you interested in the position at our school? </strong>  +      -   * What strengths will you bring to our department and/or school? In other words, tell us why should we hire you? </strong>  +      -   * If you </strong>were  to put yourself in our shoes, looking </strong>at  your CV, what do you think would make us pause, </strong>and  why is this concern not an actual concern? </strong>  +      -   * Why would you not want to come to this school? </strong>( reasons that might make you hesitate</strong>)  +                  -  ===== = Research =</strong>=====   +  =====  General </strong>=====     -  *  Describe your research (in layman's terms). </strong>  +     * </strong>**Why  are you interested in the position at our school</strong>? **</strong>     -  * Why  is your research important</strong>?   +     </strong>* What  strengths will you bring </strong>to  our department and/or school</strong>?  In other words, tell us why should we hire you</strong>?     -  * What  were your contributions </strong>to  your research</strong>?  </strong>  +     </strong>*  If </strong>you  were to put yourself </strong>in our  shoes, looking at your CV, what do you think would make us pause, and why is this concern not an actual concern</strong>?     -   * What are your research plans for the next 2-3 (5) years</strong>?   +     </strong>*  Why would </strong>you  not want to come to this school? </strong>( reasons that might make you hesitate</strong>)  </strong>    -  *  How do </strong>you  intend on conduct research, knowing that you may be the only person in your area </strong>in our  department</strong>?   +     * **Do you have any questions for us</strong>? **</strong>    -  *  How will </strong>you  involve </strong>( non-PhD</strong>)  students at the undergraduate (and Masters level, depending on the school) in your research</strong>?  +                  -  ===== = Teaching =</strong>=====   +  =====  Research </strong>=====     -  *  Tell us of a time and a specific example when you had trouble explaining a concept and then later found a better way of explaining it. </strong>  +     </strong>* * *Describe your research </strong>( in layman's terms</strong>) .*</strong>*     -  * ( Variant of the same thing</strong>)  Tell us about your teaching philosophy: describe a moment when you were particularly effective at teaching and what was your approach/thinking? </strong>  +     </strong>*  Why is your research important</strong>?     -  *  What do you love most about teaching?</strong>   +     </strong>* What  were your contributions </strong>to  your research</strong>?     -  *  What courses do you want to teach</strong>?   +     * *</strong>*What are  your research plans for the next 2-3 (5) years</strong>? **</strong>     -  * What  courses are you able </strong>to  teach</strong>?   +     </strong>*  How do </strong>you  intend on conducting research, knowing that you may </strong>be  the only person </strong>in your area  in our department</strong>?     -  * What  courses </strong>are  you not willing to teach</strong>?   +     </strong>*  Given that the teaching load is 2 </strong>courses  a semester, and we have no PhD students (to use as minions), how do </strong>you  plan on remaining active </strong>in  your research while offering our undergrads excellent instruction</strong>?     -  *  Will </strong>you be  comfortable teaching a course not </strong>in your area  of expertise</strong>?   +     </strong>*  Given that the </strong>teaching  load is 4 courses a semester, and we have no PhD </strong>students  (to use as minions), how do you plan on remaining active in your research while offering our undergrads excellent instruction</strong>?     -  *  What </strong>courses  would </strong>you  be interested </strong>in  developing</strong>?   +     </strong>*  **How will </strong>you  involve (non-PhD) students at </strong>the  undergraduate (and Masters level, depending on the school) in your research</strong>? **</strong>     -  *  Cal States: How do you deal with </strong>teaching students  of different levels of ability</strong>?   +     </strong>*  What equipment do </strong>you  need </strong>to  do your research? (Cal State)</strong>    -  *  What are </strong>you  like in </strong>the  classroom</strong>?   +      -  *  Describe how </strong>you  prepare </strong>to  teach for a class you have never taught before.</strong>  +                  -  ======  Other </strong>======   +  =====  Teaching </strong>== === </strong>    -  * What would you do to help mentor students from under-represented minorities and women?   +     * Tell us of a time and a specific example when you had trouble explaining a concept and then later found a better way of explaining it. </strong>    -  * What is your ideal academic environment?   +     * (Variant of the same thing) Tell us about your teaching philosophy: describe a moment when you were particularly effective at teaching and what was your approach/thinking? </strong>    -  * How will you adjust from your current environment to  teaching </strong>at our school?   +     * What do you love most about teaching? </strong>    -  * How will you contribute to our school's mission statement?  +     * **What courses do you want to teach?** </strong>       +     * What courses are you able to teach? </strong>       +     * What courses are you not willing to teach? </strong>       +     * **Will you be comfortable teaching a course not in your area of expertise?** </strong>       +     * What courses would you be interested in developing? </strong>       +     * **How do you deal with teaching students of different levels of ability? (Cal State)** </strong>       +     * What are you like in the classroom? </strong>       +     * Describe how you prepare to teach for a class you have never taught before. </strong>       +    </strong>       +   ===== Other (rarely asked) </strong>=====        +     </strong>* What would you do to help mentor students from under-represented minorities and women?        +     </strong>* What is your ideal academic environment?        +     </strong>* How will you adjust from your current environment to  working </strong>at our school?        +     </strong>* How will you contribute to our school's mission statement?  (Jesuit school)</strong>     
   
  

  
    
